  array('post_name' => 'hm-collaborates-with-giambattista-valli-for-their-new-collection','post_title' => 'H&M Collaborates with Giambattista Valli for their New Collection','post_content' => 'Swedish high-street fashion chain H&amp;M has joined hands with Paris based couturier Giambattista Valli for its 19th annual clothing collaboration with a designer label.  The collection titled Project Love, was revealed during the 72nd annual Cannes Film Festival at the 26th annual amfAR Gala. Kendell Jenner surprised fans from around the world when she dropped by the gala dinner in one of the limited editions pieces from the collection. Valli also dressed his muses Chris Lee, Ross Lynch, Chiara Ferragni, Singer H.E.R. and Bianca Brandolini  in his limited edition pieces.

https://www.instagram.com/p/Bx5X1X7Iymc/
<h4 style="text-align: center;">“I am excited about this collaboration,” said the designer. “H&amp;M gives me the opportunity to bring my vision of style and my celebration of beauty to a wider audience. The goal is to share my love for beauty and to be able to be a part of everyone’s ‘happy moments’, to help create love stories around the world.</h4>
Giambattista Valli is the master of beauty and sophistication. The collection His inspired by is signature tulle layered style and will have party dresses. For a first for Valli, he will be dabbling into men\'s wear and release a number of tailored pieces for men.

https://www.instagram.com/p/Bx4O12eoG7S

Ann-Sofie Johansson, H&amp;M’s creative adviser, accompanied  Valli and his models at the gala. She seemed visibly excited about the new collaboration.
<h4 style="text-align: center;">“Giambattista is really a master when it comes to beauty and glamour and sophistication, we’re really happy to be working with him,” she told <em>Vogue</em>. “We always want to have different takes on the collaborations. This is different compared to Moschino last year. It’s the first time we’re working with someone doing couture.”</h4>
https://www.instagram.com/p/Bx0tbzElUNJ

&nbsp;

Couture at H&amp;M prices. The collection is priced between $18 to $649. The collection will drop in stored and online from November 7, 2019. But there is a surprise for all their fans from around the world. In a first by H&amp;M, they are pre-dropping a limited edition collection on 25th May. The collection contains a few of the pieces from the entire collection and will be available in 12 stores around the world and on H&amp;M\'s online website.','post_excerpt' => '','post_date' => '2019-06-03 19:00:38'),
  array('post_name' => 'the-different-body-types-and-shapes-for-different-women','post_title' => 'The Different Body Types and Shapes for Different Women','post_content' => 'How many times have we asked ourselves "why that dress suits her and not in me?" As already mentioned in previous <a href="https://www.ifashionnetwork.com/trends-empowering-women/">articles,</a> dressing is not only putting clothes on our body, but also, it is the most direct way to communicate who we are every day.
We are not talking about dressing up with fancy and expensive clothes, or second hand, we are talking about dressing in a way that our way of thinking, of expressing, our personality is reflected in each garment or accessories that we carry. Our way of dressing can talk about our profession, about our hobbies, about political ideologies, or if we are those addicted to fashion that follows each trend.

&nbsp;

[caption id="attachment_20274" align="aligncenter" width="1024"]<img class="wp-image-20274 size-full" src="https://www.ifashionnetwork.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/DSC1227.jpg" alt="" width="1024" height="683" /> Image Source: Heather Hazzan and Lily Cummings[/caption]

How many times do we find ourselves with certain discomforts with some garments that do not fit in our body, that we feel uncomfortable when we wear them. And here is when we ask ourselves, Why My Body, And Not Hers?
<h5 style="text-align: center;">The clothes speak, and much more than we think.</h5>
[caption id="attachment_20271" align="aligncenter" width="1024"]<img class="wp-image-20271 size-full" src="https://www.ifashionnetwork.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/Esteban-Emilio-555_R1-3.jpg" alt="" width="1024" height="590" /> Image Source: Heather Hazzan and Lily Cummings[/caption]

To be a little more specific, the parts of the body that most identify us and matter when buying clothes are Shoulders, Bust, Waist, Hip. These four parts of our body are going to help us to know WHAT TYPE OF BODY WE HAVE, and why we wear that dress well and  not at all. We have five types of female morphology types of body and their main characteristics and to give you a clearer example, we will put a celebrity as an example for each one.
<h2><strong>Body Rectangle:</strong> Well-proportioned shoulders and hips, at the same height, but lack waist. The example we are going to give is that of Gigi Hadid. With this image, what we show, reinforces her waist with some ties to mark it and that stands out inside her body.</h2>
[caption id="attachment_20212" align="aligncenter" width="1365"]<img class="wp-image-20212 size-full" src="https://www.ifashionnetwork.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/p2180322-3.jpg" alt="" width="1365" height="2048" /> Victoria´s Fashion Week Ny / 2018[/caption]
<h2 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Hourglass:</strong> Shoulders and hips of the same width, have a well-marked waist. The clearest example is that of Kim Kardashian who dazzles us with her perfect silhouette.</h2>
[caption id="attachment_20249" align="aligncenter" width="2064"]<img class="wp-image-20249 size-full" src="https://www.ifashionnetwork.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/ab6fedaa39495662143d76a4adf5a32d.jpg" alt="" width="2064" height="2981" /> Kim Kardashian / GC images[/caption]
<h2 style="text-align: center;">Triangle: A very common silhouette, women caderonas, a lot of leg and bum and very narrow shoulders. Beyonce is one of our star examples. With its prominent hips and definite shoulders.</h2>
[caption id="attachment_20251" align="aligncenter" width="2000"]<img class="wp-image-20251 size-full" src="https://www.ifashionnetwork.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/Esteban-Emilio-555_R1.jpg" alt="" width="2000" height="3000" /> Queen B hippie chic- 2016 - Getty Images[/caption]
<h2 style="text-align: center;">Inverted Triangle: Narrow hips and well-marked shoulders, This silhouette is very common in women who exercise.</h2>
[caption id="attachment_20252" align="aligncenter" width="1826"]<img class="wp-image-20252 size-full" src="https://www.ifashionnetwork.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/Esteban-Emilio-555_R1-1.jpg" alt="" width="1826" height="3000" /> Reese Witherspoon / 10th Annual Avon Foundation For Women Gala / NY 2010[/caption]
<h2 style="text-align: center;">Oval: A waist with more circumference than the bust and the hip. The hips are wide and the upper thighs are quite wide.</h2>
[caption id="attachment_20267" align="aligncenter" width="1200"]<img class="wp-image-20267 size-full" src="https://www.ifashionnetwork.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/Esteban-Emilio-555_R1-2.jpg" alt="" width="1200" height="1801" /> Jennifer Hudson at Brit Awards / London / 2018[/caption]

This is not an article to show you what kind of bodies celebrities have. This is the moment when you  run to the mirror - preferably naked - and have an eye to see which silhouette fits with our body.
The main idea is that we can see that we all have different bodies and that our challenge is to be able to be those women, strong, independent, before a society that imposes,  knowing who we are outside and inside.
Knowing our strengths and weaknesses is what makes us the women we want to be. Therefore, with this article, we show you that each woman is different. That each one has an attribute that differentiates it from the other and that thanks to that attribute (we must always see everything positive) we can be who we want to be if we know how to identify it and empower it.

As we showed in the pictures of the celebrities, each one opted for a wardrobe that favors they taking into account their body\'s morphology. No morphology is better or worse than the other. Women just have to understand what kind of body they have, accept ourselves as we are and identify what garments are those that will make us highlight and embrace our curves.

[caption id="attachment_20273" align="aligncenter" width="1024"]<img class="wp-image-20273 size-full" src="https://www.ifashionnetwork.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/DSC1049.jpg" alt="" width="1024" height="641" /> Image Source: Heather Hazzan and Lily Cummings[/caption]','post_excerpt' => '','post_date' => '2019-06-03 20:24:53'),
  array('post_name' => 'guccis-pre-fall-19-campaign-is-all-about-the-old-world-charm','post_title' => 'Gucci\'s Pre-Fall \'19 Campaign is all about the Old World Charm','post_content' => 'When Gucci released it\'s Pre-fall\'19 collection in December, it was a very simple unveiling. 86 beautifully dressed mannequins just displayed in their Milan studio. There was no one from the design team to explain  the collection. There were no press notes to give editors and reporters clarity.The man himself, Alessandro Michele was not present. The tailoring details were refined with a mix of pattern and color and took one back to the 80\'s.

https://www.instagram.com/p/Bw68k8SnrYv/

Fast forward a few months, and once can see two different series of photo shoots launched in the month of April and May for its Pre- fall\'19 collection. For the April series of photo shoot, we see Michele\'s homage to the ancient Greek culture. Shot by Glen Luchford at the background of the temples of the Selinute Archaeological Park in Sicily, the series takes us back to the time when people would gather after banquets to chat, dance, mingle and have fun. Giving this banquet a modern twist, Michele brought hardcore punks, body builders, roller bladders and surfers dressed in brightly patterned Gucci wear to reignite that spirit for their Pre-Fall 2019 campaign.

https://www.instagram.com/p/BwUDEhSn4gj/

Another series for the Pre-fall\'19 Campaign came out in May. It showed showed Harry Styles in the lead for #GucciTailoring. The campaign is creatively visualized by creative director, Alessandro Michele. It is shot by Harmony Korine and art directed by Christopher Simmonds. The series depict Michele\'s taste for the uncoventional and antique and the news menswear formal collection is described as "contemporary layered with bright colors"

https://www.instagram.com/p/Bxw1wrnCBf7/','post_excerpt' => '','post_date' => '2019-06-03 21:11:41'),
  array('post_name' => 'fantasy-style-elements-by-hakuyo-miya-at-nyfw','post_title' => 'Fantasy Style Elements by Hakuyo Miya at NYFW','post_content' => 'Hakuyo Miya showcased for the third time at the NYFW with the approval of CAAFD ((The Council of Aspiring American Fashion Designers) for Fall/Winter \'19 showcasing. Miya used <span style="font-weight: 400;">fantasy style elements, fiery designs combining color, texture and culture into beautiful and edgy elegant pieces. His designs represented innovative lines and cuts as well as the aspect of modernism throughout the collections, features he has distinguished himself with.</span>

“The theme for this collection is “le crépuscule” (dusk, or twilight); the moment between day and night. It is a very mysterious moment; a moment that is very dear to me. Sometimes, I work all night long and there I feel something very special. I really like it.” the designer told Guild Magazine.

Born in Japan, Miya went on to <span style="font-weight: 400;">study at the Atelier Chardon Savard in Paris. This gave his work the unique French flair. his brand Mouton Blanc ( French for white sheep) is known for creating </span>women\'s ready-to-wear  perfect combinations of beautiful silhouettes of fantasy and delicate and bold fabrics. Each piece of the brand  offers a unique blend of Parisian elegance, influences of Japanese traditions and enchanting stories from Eastern Europe. Mouton Blanc has their own unique style as they use intricate lace, astonishing volumes and are on a constant search for new materials and textures, in a visual world where traditions meet the unexpected.

